  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 증민(烝民) : '
    value: 《시경(詩經)》 대아(大雅) 중의 편(篇) 이름으로 주(周)의 시조(始祖)  후직(后稷)의 공덕을 칭송한 글인데, 후직은 농사를 발달시켰으므로 후세에 곡식의 신[穀神]으로 받든다.
  - key: '[주-D002] 쌀 …… 서푼 : '
    value: 옛날에는 쌀값이 쌀수록 백성이 살기가 좋다는 것이다.
english:
  title: The Sound of Pounding Rice
  author: Seok Hwang-yeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The eldest wife pounds at the eastern mortar,
    The younger wife at the western mortar,
    The younger husband at the southern mortar,
    The eldest husband at the northern mortar.
    A little daughter steadies the pestle head,
    A small boy plays with the rice, turning the winnow.

    In her green skirt, the elder woman's hair piled high,
    Strong legs driving the mortar down steadily,
    The husbands and wives call out in surprise,
    Jesting and laughing, voices rising in a din.
    Sweat drenches their backs as they pause for breath,
    Pickingup grains to see—not quite white, not quite white.
    Still not white enough, so they pound once more,
    What toil, what labor—truly it moves the heart.

    Yet Heaven grants talent no man lacks,
    So why must poverty and wealth divide our paths?
    Though hardship and ease fall differently by lot,
    The scholar's rule and the farmer's work depend upon each other.

    Last autumn's harvest brought cheap rice to market,
    This year the hemp and wheat have flourished equally.
    The government lightens the people's burden,
    The women's winnows and men's baskets overflow with ease.
    Some pound, some winnow, some toss and scatter,
    Steam rises gently, rice billows and floats.

    The great odes sing of Yu's people, of Hou Ji's praise—
    His gifts endure for ten thousand ages unending.
    Now the villages gather their harvest bounty,
    The four seas rest in peace, not a speck of dust rises.
    I pray each year brings the world such harmony,
    That rice costs but three coins—as the ancients wished.
  footnotes:
    - 'Yu''s people (增民) and Hou Ji (后稷): References to classical Chinese poetry celebrating agricultural prosperity and the legendary culture hero who developed agriculture, venerated as the grain god.'
    - 'Three coins: An allusion to an ancient standard for rice prices; cheap rice symbolized prosperity and the people''s well-being.'
